{"entity": "High-Risk AI Systems", "type": "artifact", "description": "High-Risk AI Systems are a specific category of artificial intelligence systems identified by their potential to pose significant harmful impacts on health, safety, fundamental rights, and public interests within the Union. These systems are characterized by their potential adverse effects on democracy, the rule of law, individual freedoms, and accountability, particularly when deployed in sensitive areas such as law enforcement, migration, justice, biometrics, critical infrastructure, and education.

Under the applicable Regulation, High-Risk AI Systems are classified based on specific criteria, including those listed in Annex III and Annex I, or those serving as safety components of products covered by Union harmonisation legislation requiring third-party conformity assessments. According to Article 6(1) and Article 6(2), these systems are subject to mandatory requirements and harmonised rules for market placement and use, which apply even if the systems are released under free and open-source licenses.

To ensure a high level of protection, High-Risk AI Systems must adhere to strict technical and organizational obligations. These include mandatory bias detection and correction, transparency, comprehensive technical documentation, and the implementation of automatic event recording (logs). They must meet rigorous standards for accuracy, robustness, and cybersecurity to prevent harmful behavior. Furthermore, providers are required to implement post-market monitoring and corrective actions to ensure ongoing compliance.

Compliance for High-Risk AI Systems often involves conformity assessments and certification by notified bodies. Systems listed in Annex III must be registered at a national level and in the EU database, detailing their functionalities and use cases. Additionally, these systems may be subject to strict testing in real-world conditions. When the outputs of these systems serve as the primary basis for a deployer's decision, affected persons may be entitled to an explanation. Stricter compliance requirements are especially emphasized when these systems are utilized by public authorities."}
