{"entity": "AI Office", "type": "organization", "description": "The AI Office is a Union-level body established by Commission Decision to develop expertise and capabilities in artificial intelligence and contribute to the implementation of Union law. Operating as a function of the Commission—to which references in the Regulation are construed—the AI Office is tasked with the implementation, monitoring, and supervision of AI governance, AI systems, and general-purpose AI models. It possesses the powers of a market surveillance authority, enabling it to monitor compliance, investigate infringements, conduct evaluations, and request corrective measures from providers.

Regarding general-purpose AI models, the AI Office acts as a primary regulatory body. It is responsible for receiving notifications, mandates, and reports, and it requires providers to make technical documentation available upon request. To ensure consistency and compliance, the AI Office provides standardized templates for training summaries and monitors the placement of these models on the market. It further engages with industry and the scientific community to inform benchmarks and thresholds for AI models, while being supported and advised by a Scientific Panel regarding enforcement and implementation.

The AI Office also plays a critical role in establishing regulatory frameworks and best practices. It facilitates the creation of codes of practice—specifically for the detection and labeling of AI content—and assesses the suitability of harmonized standards. Additionally, it develops and recommends voluntary model terms for contracts between high-risk AI system providers and third parties, and requests updated guidelines from the Commission.

Beyond model supervision, the AI Office supports the broader AI ecosystem by providing coordination for joint investigations and promoting best practices in public procurement via an information platform and standardized templates. It supports national competent authorities in developing AI regulatory sandboxes, maintains a public list of these sandboxes, and receives related notifications and reports."}
