{"entity": "High-Risk AI System", "type": "artifact", "description": "A High-Risk AI System is a specific category of artificial intelligence system classified based on its purpose and its potential to pose significant risks of harm to the health, safety, or fundamental rights of persons, as determined by the severity and probability of that harm. Under the governing Regulation, this classification includes systems listed in Annex III—such as those utilized in law enforcement, border management, justice, and democracy—as well as systems used in activities performed via contracts between Union operators and third-country operators.

To mitigate these risks, High-Risk AI Systems are subject to stringent obligations and strict compliance requirements detailed in Chapter III, Section 2 of the Regulation. These include mandatory risk management processes, high standards for data governance and quality, bias mitigation, and the maintenance of comprehensive technical documentation. Such systems must be designed for consistency, accuracy, robustness, and cybersecurity throughout their entire lifecycle. Furthermore, they require the implementation of human oversight, the keeping of automatically generated logs, and the provision of strict usage instructions.

Before being placed on the market or put into service, a High-Risk AI System must undergo a conformity assessment and a declaration of conformity to ensure it meets all safety and regulatory standards. Compliance often necessitates a quality management system, testing in real-world conditions, and the attainment of CE marking. Additionally, these systems must be registered in the EU database. In certain instances, they are subject to fundamental rights impact assessments and technical testing to detect potential infringements.

The supervision of High-Risk AI Systems involves cooperation between the AI Office and market surveillance authorities for compliance evaluations. Deployers and providers are held to specific obligations regarding transparency and reporting. Failure to adhere to these regulatory requirements may result in the system being brought into conformity, or facing more severe actions such as restriction, prohibition, or recall from the market."}
