{"entity": "Union Harmonisation Legislation", "type": "content", "description": "Union Harmonisation Legislation refers to the body of European Union laws designed to ensure consistency, safety, and the free movement of products within the internal market. This general framework establishes common standards and harmonized rules for various products or devices, including medical devices, and defines critical safety and risk criteria. It also introduces essential regulatory concepts, such as the notion of substantial modification for products.

Within the context of the AI Regulation, Union Harmonisation Legislation is used to align the Regulation with other Union standards and ensure enforcement and consistency. Specifically, the legal frameworks listed in Annex I are utilized to determine if an AI system is classified as high-risk, particularly when the AI system serves as a safety component or is part of a product that undergoes a third-party conformity assessment.

The legislation is further categorized within Annex I. Legal frameworks listed in Section A govern products placed on the market or put into service, including those for which high-risk AI systems may act as safety components. This section may also establish existing monitoring systems and plans for such AI systems. Meanwhile, frameworks listed in Section B cover specific products and integrate requirements for high-risk AI systems.

